    },
    "kf-2a47a8ff42": {
      "id": "kf-2a47a8ff42",
      "name": "Quick Capture (Second Brain)",
      "parentId": "sec-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>What:</strong> One-keystroke capture from anywhere in the app. Hit Cmd+Shift+I, type or paste, hit Enter — it lands in your Second Brain Inbox. No need to be inside any specific outline.</p><p><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Memory research shows we lose ~50% of new information within an hour, 70% within a day. The friction between a thought and its capture is where value dies. Quick Capture turns capture into a reflex, not a chore.</p><p><strong>Differentiator:</strong> Every successful note tool (Apple Notes, Drafts, Bear, Notion) has a scratchpad. IdiamPro's version lands the captured thought directly into the AI-searchable Second Brain — instant input, AI-powered retrieval.</p>",
      "isExpanded": false
    },
    "kf-eb8cb625fa": {
      "id": "kf-eb8cb625fa",
      "name": "Second Brain Dashboard",
      "parentId": "sec-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>What:</strong> A visual home for your Second Brain showing total entries, recent saves with snippets, and a \"revisit pile\" of older content worth re-engaging with.</p><p><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Capture without retrieval is a graveyard (the Evernote lesson). The dashboard gives users the feeling that their effort compounds — visible proof that yesterday's save matters today. It transforms Second Brain from a sink into a living archive.</p><p><strong>Differentiator:</strong> Most outline tools are write-only. The Dashboard is the resting state — the place users open the app to be reminded of what they care about.</p>",
      "isExpanded": false
    },
    "kf-eac19fb868": {
      "id": "kf-eac19fb868",
      "name": "Smart Auto-Tagging (Second Brain)",
      "parentId": "sec-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>What:</strong> When you save to Second Brain, AI suggests 1–3 tags from the content. Accept, edit, or skip — tags persist as metadata and power future filtering and search.</p><p><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Manual tagging fails universally — folders go stale, categories drift, taxonomies collapse. Asking the user to organize at save time breaks the capture habit. AI silently doing it means the system gets smarter the more it's used, with no effort from the user.</p><p><strong>Differentiator:</strong> Every PKM tool has tagging. Almost none have AI doing it for you. This is the AI-native value proposition that justifies the Premium tier: not \"here's a chat dropped in,\" but \"the tool that organizes itself.\"</p>",
      "isExpanded": false
    },
    "kf-livebooks": {
      "id": "kf-livebooks",
      "name": "LIVE BOOKS (proposed)",
      "parentId": "sec-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "document",
      "content": "<p><strong>Status:</strong> Proposed feature — added to roadmap 2026-05-13. Cost model resolved 2026-05-13. All 6 design questions CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15.</p><p><strong>What:</strong> Take any outline and refresh its content against the latest information on the internet. Available to both authors and readers of an outline, against any outline.</p><p><strong>Candidate tagline:</strong> \"Keep your knowledge base current with the latest from the internet.\"</p><p><strong>Triggers / use cases:</strong></p><ul><li><p>User upgrades their AI engine (new API key, new model version)</p></li><li><p>Time passes — technologies mature, cultural references shift, facts evolve</p></li><li><p>Reader of a third-party outline wants the latest take on the topic, not the author's frozen snapshot</p></li></ul><p><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Static documents go stale. Today's outline about \"the latest AI models\" is wrong in six weeks. LIVE BOOKS turns an outline into a living document that ages well, automatically.</p><p><strong>Differentiator:</strong> Wikipedia is community-edited but slow; AI chat is fresh but ephemeral. LIVE BOOKS is the third path — your personal structured knowledge, kept current by AI on demand, with author and reader both empowered to refresh.</p><p><strong>RESOLVED — Pricing &amp; cost model (signed off 2026-05-13):</strong></p><ul><li><p><strong>BYOK (Bring Your Own Key) launch posture.</strong> User provides their own Anthropic / OpenAI / Google API key; IdiamPro never touches vendor billing.</p></li><li><p><strong>Flat software service fee</strong> (target ~$9.99/month) gates LIVE BOOKS access. Covers our development, hosting, support, feature improvement.</p></li><li><p><strong>Legal posture:</strong> avoids reseller TOS issues with Anthropic / OpenAI / Google entirely — user has direct relationship with vendor.</p></li><li><p><strong>Engineering obligations:</strong> secure API-key storage (encrypted at rest, never logged, key rotation, secure recovery).</p></li><li><p><strong>Audience scope:</strong> power users at launch (BYOK friction excludes ~70% of casual users by design).</p></li><li><p><strong>Managed-credits tier (bundled refreshes, no key required) deferred to v2</strong> — only if BYOK demand proves the market.</p></li></ul><p><strong>Design Decisions (closed 2026-05-15):</strong></p><p><strong>Feature concept:</strong> Take any outline and refresh its content against the latest information on the internet so static documents don't go stale. Manual and user-controlled. Local-first — v1 has NO dependency on the unbuilt collaboration feature.</p><ul><li><p><strong>Q1 — Refresh Scope — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> Trigger is MANUAL ONLY, invoked by the author or reader; no scheduled or automatic refresh in v1. A refresh dialog is shown; the default scope is the currently selected node PLUS all of its descendants, so selecting the root node refreshes the entire outline. Frequency is manual invocation only to start — no caps and no automation.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q2 — Diff / Review Step — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> By default, always: preview → user approves → then implemented. If the change is not accepted it is rejected and nothing is altered. Auto-apply is NEVER the default; it is an explicit opt-in the user must deliberately select to relinquish control for that specific refresh, and it covers the selected node plus its descendants.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q3 — Author vs Reader Versions — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> v1 is a personal fork — a reader's refresh creates their own copy and the author's canonical version is never touched by a reader. This is satisfied for free by the existing file export/import model (no sharing infrastructure needed; LIVE BOOKS v1 has no dependency on the unbuilt collaboration feature, task #12). Deferred to the collaboration feature: contribute-back — and its model is already decided: a collaborator's edits are OFFERED to the originator, who approves or rejects them (the same approve pattern as Q2).</p></li><li><p><strong>Q4 — Citations — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> Mandatory citations on every refreshed node; they cannot be turned off. Displayed as compact inline source references (a \"Sources\" affordance, not body-text clutter). Source URLs and metadata are stored on the node so they persist and travel with the outline.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q5 — Manual-Edit Conflict Handling — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> Auto-skip manually-edited nodes by default. The refresh dialog shows which nodes were skipped because the user had edited them, with a per-node explicit opt-in override. Requires tracking a \"user-edited\" flag per node.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q6 — Model Attribution — CLOSED — decided 2026-05-15:</strong> Surface model attribution on every refresh, attributing whichever model did the refresh (Claude, Gemini, or local), shown unobtrusively next to the citations (e.g., \"Refreshed with Claude · 4 sources\"). Pre-launch action item: verify the exact required wording and placement for Claude with Anthropic per their usage policy.</p></li><li><p><strong>Q7 — Node Update Behavior — CLOSED (decided 2026-05-15):</strong> Default = MERGE/AUGMENT — the AI revises the node in place: preserves still-accurate content, updates stale parts, and folds in genuinely new information; it does NOT discard the node and regenerate wholesale. An explicit 'Overwrite / regenerate from scratch' option is available in the refresh dialog for when the user wants a clean rewrite of a section. Both operate behind the Q2 preview/approve gate, with per-node granularity inherited from the existing preview UI.</p></li></ul><p><strong>Implementation implications (for the implement-LIVE-BOOKS task):</strong></p><ul><li><p>New per-node data: a user-edited flag, citation/source metadata, and model-used metadata.</p></li><li><p>New refresh dialog UI: a scope selector defaulting to the selected node plus its descendants; a preview/diff with per-node accept/reject; a skipped-edited-nodes list with per-node opt-in; and an optional auto-apply opt-in.</p></li><li><p>Uses the existing AI provider abstraction plus web retrieval.</p></li><li><p>No sharing infrastructure required for v1.</p></li></ul>",
      "isExpanded": false
    },
    "sp-multilingual-collab-board-20260515": {
      "id": "sp-multilingual-collab-board-20260515",
      "name": "Multilingual Collaboration Board — flagship selling point (2026-05-15)",
      "content": "<p><strong>Multilingual Collaboration Board — flagship selling point (2026-05-15)</strong></p><p>The Multilingual Collaboration Board is a flagship category differentiator. Legacy GDSS (GroupSystems lineage) was effectively monolingual; this is one shared collaboration board where multilingual teams think together — every participant brainstorms, comments, reads, and votes in their OWN language, and foreign-language documents are auto-translated and woven directly into the group's shared outline. This targets multinational enterprises, research consortia, NGOs, and cross-border legal/M&A teams, and strengthens the Level 3 enterprise B2B pricing story. It composes from already-designed pieces: the language-translation engine (task #52) + the LIVE BOOKS transform engine + the Level 3 collaboration board (task #12). A lighter version — integrating foreign-language source documents into a single user's own outlines — is also a selling point for the MAIN app, enabled by #52.</p><p><em>Selling-point sentence: \"One shared board where multilingual teams think together — everyone contributes and reads in their own language, and foreign-language documents are translated and woven directly into the group's outline.\"</em></p><p><em>Tagline: \"Multilingual minds, one shared brain — no language left out.\"</em></p><p><em>Fuller value prop: \"The collaboration board erases the language barrier in group work: every participant brainstorms, comments, and votes in their native language; every foreign-language source is auto-translated and integrated in place; and the result is one structured shared body of knowledge the whole team owns — regardless of the languages they speak.\"</em></p><p>Note: the lighter single-user form — integrating foreign-language source documents directly into one user's own outlines — is a selling point for the MAIN app, tied to the language-translation feature (task #52).</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "sp-root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "prefix": "0"
    }
  },
